savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Forming-a-glycosidic-bond.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Glycosidic bonds form through condensation reactions, during which a water molecule is released. When two glucose molecules are joined by a glycosidic bond, the resulting disaccharide is maltose.</b></i></p><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Glycosidic bonds in a Polysaccharide" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="506" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Glycosidic-bonds-in-a-Polysaccharide.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Glycosidic bonds can link monosaccharides together to form polysaccharides such as amylopectin, a form of starch. Amylopectin contains 1,4 and 1,6 glycosidic bonds.</b></i></p><ul><li><p>There are many different types of monosaccharide, which join together to form <b>different disaccharides, </b>e.g.</p><ul><li><p>Two molecules of glucose join to form <b>maltose</b></p></li><li><p>Glucose joins with the monosaccharide fructose to form <b>sucrose</b></p></li><li><p>Glucose joins with the monosaccharide galactose to form <b>lactose</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="breaking-the-glycosidic-bond">Breaking the glycosidic bond</h4><ul><li><p>The glycosidic bond is broken when <b>water is added </b>in a<b> hydrolysis reaction</b></p><ul><li><p>Hydro = water</p></li><li><p>Lysis = to break</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Examples of hydrolytic reactions include the <b>digestion of food</b> in the alimentary tract and the <b>breakdown of stored carbohydrates</b> in muscle and liver cells for use in cellular <span class="popovers" data-content="The chemical process by which energy is released from glucose to produce ATP inside living cells. Aerobic respiration requires oxygen, while anaerobic respiration does not." data-title="Respiration" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">respiration</span></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Breaking of a glycosidic bond" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="892" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Breaking-of-a-glycosidic-bond.png 384w, https